eye (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to be involved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left third cranial nerve","Right third cranial nerve","Left sixth cranial nerve","Left sympathetic chain","Right sympathetic chain"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of Horner\u0027s syndrome on the right side - ptosis and miosis (constricted pupil). Horner\u0027s syndrome occurs due to interruption of sympathetic nerve supply to the eye and face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight sympathetic chain\u003C/strong\u003E involvement is the correct diagnosis, causing the characteristic triad of ptosis (from denervation of M\u00fcller\u0027s muscle), miosis (from denervation of iris dilator), and anhidrosis (though not mentioned in this case). The concurrent hoarseness suggests recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement, raising concern for tumour recurrence or progression, possibly a Pancoast tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft third cranial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E palsy would cause ptosis and pupillary abnormalities on the left side, not the right. Additionally, third nerve palsy typically causes a dilated or normal pupil, not miosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight third cranial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E palsy would be on the correct side but would present with a dilated or normal pupil, not the miosis seen here. It would also cause additional features like extraocular muscle weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft sixth cranial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E palsy would affect the left eye and would not cause ptosis or pupillary changes. Instead, it would cause lateral rectus weakness resulting in impaired abduction and diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft sympathetic chain\u003C/strong\u003E involvement would cause Horner\u0027s syndrome on the left side, not the right as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Horner\u0027s syndrome presents with the triad of ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis due to interruption of sympathetic nerve supply.","Recent onset Horner\u0027s syndrome with hoarseness may indicate an underlying Pancoast tumour compressing both sympathetic chain and recurrent laryngeal nerve.","Third nerve palsy can be distinguished from Horner\u0027s syndrome by pupil size - dilated or normal in third nerve palsy versus constricted in Horner\u0027s."],"references":["Martin TJ. Horner Syndrome: A Clinical Review. ACS Chem Neurosci. 2018 Feb 21;9(2):177-186. doi: 10.1021/acschemneuro.7b00405. Epub 2017 Dec 20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16985"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16985"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5865c815-f470-41a6-9d2c-727d473c5ffb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5865c815-f470-41a6-9d2c-727d473c5ffb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":304}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T19:31:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T19:33:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"704"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82497"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"met